@node Introduction

@{b}Introduction@{ub}@{par}
@{par}
BlueEyes are little colourful Eyes for the Amiga. Before BlueEyes, doesn`t exists
such @{i}colourful @{ui} Eyes on the Amiga. Thats why we started to programme BlueEyes.@{par}
BlueEyes requests its needed colours from AmigaOS on the start, this makes it possible
that BlueEyes apears almost in right colours.@{par}
You can control most of the features of BlueEyes with @{" Tooltypes " link ToolTypes}.@{par}
Since Version 2.0 of BlueEyes, the eyes looking still to the mousepointer until the eyelid wink.
I think that all the other Eye-Tools can`t compete with this feature!@{par}
@{par}
Thanks to Dirk Schmidt, Mario Gräfe & Sascha Aderhold for testing.
Thanks to Michael Hohmann for the idea to give the @{" BackColor " link ToolTypes} Tooltype
negative values.
@endnode

@node Blue

@{b}BlueEye@{ub}@{par}
@{par}
BlueEye are nearly the same as BlueEyes but with only one Eye.@{par}
You can use it exactly like BlueEyes, but it is possible to run more
than one Eye simultaneousely!@{par}
It`s very funny.@{par}
@endnode

@node Install

@{b}Installation of BlueEyes@{ub}@{par}
@{par}
You may drag BlueEyes in the WBStartup drawer or in any other drawer.
Now you should set the @{" ToolTypes " link ToolTypes}.@{par}

BlueEyes is a WB-Tool and you should start them from WB. For CLI-Tigers (they are
very dangerous) exists the possibility to start BlueEyes from Shell.
The arguments are the same as @{" ToolTypes " link ToolTypes}.@{par}

   example: run >NIL: BlueEyes XPos=10 YPos=100 Backcolor=1@{par}

You can use the arguments in that order you like. But you should use
@{i} run >NIL: @{ui} to disconnect BlueEyes from Shell.@{par}

BlueEyes comes with a NewIcon. NewIcon is © by Nicola Salmoria and it is very great.@{par}
@endnode

